{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bubley_ver02/data/sn82016181/00529040076/1945083101/1849.xml":{"full_text":"Austria's Plight\n___________ A USTRIA today is probably the mast\ntragic country in all Europe, ac--\ncording to observers recently returned\nJM MJ* S from the scene.\nIn Vienna some 20 years ago. I\nME\u00ae, talked with Dr Michael Hainisch. the:-.\nPresident of the Austrian Republic.\nLeading me over to a large wall-map\nof central Europe. lie pointed at a\n4 tadpole-shaped area in the center\n\"See that.' he said. \"That is Austria\nMIM|L But it Is not a country. It is a fish\nout of water, and a fish out of water\n\u2014A cannot live.\u201d\nWhat he meant was, the Treaty of St. Germain had so\ntrimmed down Austrian territory that she was no longer\nan economic entity. There was only Vienna, one of the\nworld\u2019s largest capital, surrounded by a hinterland.\nToday Austria is still further subdivided. More than\nhalf is occupied by the Red army. The rest\u2014split* into\nthree parts\u2014is occupied by the Americans, British and\nFrench. More or less all have looted their zones pretty\nthoroly and flooded them with paper money.\nTHE American zone, according to the report, seerns to be\nfaring like the others. The food situation is some\nbetter because the Americans are bringing in mast of their\nown, while the others are living off the land. This latter\nis especially true of the Russian zone.\nAmericans are said to make no difference between\nAustrians and Germans. If anything, the Austrians feel\nthey are getting the worst of it. One Austrian resistance\nleader, for instance, complained that he had been ordered\nout of an American office by a German whom he recog\nnized as a former local Gestapo official.\nAU sorts of stories harmful to America are said to be\nmaking the rounds. One of these is that Austrian public\nutilities are to be turned over permanently to American\nHow Many Jobless?\nYOU can be scared stiff or pushed\nslightly to the optimistic side, ac\ncording to which set of figures you\nhear around Washington on the prob-\n_ able number of jobless when reconver-\ns on unemployment gets to its worst.\nThe most authoritative official esti\nmate, out in the open, is the one given\nby John W Snyder, director of War\nMobilization and Reconversion, before\nthe House Ways and Means Committee,\nin urging Federal reinforcement of state\nunemployment benefits He said the\njobless will probably number six million\nby Jan. 1. and perhaps eight million next spring as result\nof many men getting out of the armed forces.\nSome Government statisticians who keep their fingers\nconstantly on this particular pulse do not support Mr.\nSynder\u2019s eight million figure. They say it may never go\nabove six million in the post-war period unless we have\nextremely bad luck in the industrial turn-over.\nFor comparison: Figures of the U. S. Bureau of Labor\nStatistics show there were 11,900,000 unemployed in 1932.\nand 12.500.000 in 1933. There were almost as many in the\ntwo following years. In 1938 there were almost 10 million\nand in 1939 almost nine million.\n'PHUS the highest official estimate of next year's unem\nployment (Mr. Snyder\u2019s) is only two-thirds of the\nfigure at the depth of the big depression. It is approxi\nmately equal to the 7H million average of unemployed\nduring 1940, the year when the New Deal won its third\npresidential victory.\nThe estimate of eight million unemployed around next\nMarch is accepted by the American Federation of Labor,\nwhich states: \"After that we should be over the hump\nLiberal Businessmen\nTHE new organization of liberal busi\nnessmen that made its bow on the\nX Yk Washington stage recently is named\nJ 1 the New Council of American Business.\nV First president is Clarence Avildsen of\n5 7 Chicago, chairman of the board and\n5^ \u2019W? 70 P\u00ae r cent ow ner of the Republic Drill\nToo l Corp., a three-million-dollar\n\u2019jLfc concern.\nr Why another organization of busi-\nnessmen? you ask.\nML President Avildsen. in u.iveihng\n^Hncab declared flatly that the Un.ted\nStates Chamber of Commerce and the\nNational Association of Manufacturers are not as liberal\nand progressive as they should be.\"\nUSCC and the NAM have, of course, been called worse\n1 nings than that by many left-wingers. But to have a\ngroup of businessmen break away from their traditional\nleadership and go in for some plain and fancy free think\nmg is something different. Avildsen's statement strikes\nle keynote for the new organization, however, putting it\non the level of the American Lawyers Guild, which broke\nfrom the conservative American Bar Association.\n\\1 HILE the New Council of American Business is not a\npolitical organization, its formation really began\nl en the presidential campaign was at its height. At\nr!, \u2019t time a Businessman for Roosevelt and several other\nc Jickie political organizations were dreamed up. Idea was\nJ IVe Democratic businessmen something to belong to\nant. offset Republican charges that Roosevelt's fourth\ntenn drive was entirely the work of the CIO Political\nAction Committee.\nBy William Philip Simms\ninterests. The Tauernwerke. at Salzburg, according to the\ntale, is to be dispased of in that fashion. It is the larg^t\nelectric plant in Austria.\nA NOTHER thing that is hurting our prestige, it is\nr*. stated, is the presence of politicaUy-minded officers\nwho lean strongly toward the left wing or out-and-out\nCommunism. This seems to be especially unwelcome be\ncause the American zone is overwhelmingly Catholic.\nIn Salzburg, the American authorities are reported to\nhave suggested setting up a district government this fall\nwithout an election. The plan was to allot 11 seats to the\nCatholic Volkspartei in place of the 14 it won at the last\nelection; 11 to the Socialists, who had had only 7, and 8\nto the Communists, who had had none at all.\nHERE. I am informed, are seven pleas advanced by the\nAustrian people:\n1. As Austria was Hitlers first victim, even before\nCzechoslovakia. Austrians want to be treated as Austrians,\nnot as Nazis or Germans.\n2. That Austrian economy be placed in the hands of\nlocal Austrians.\n3. That German aliens, mostly Nazis, be sent out of\nAustria.\n4 That freedom of speech, press and assembly be re\nestablished so that politically Austrians will not be forced\nby foreign troops into ideologies which, to them, are\nunwelcome.\n5. That assurances be given that Austrian utilities will\nnot be turned over to foreign concerns.\n6 That U. S. Treasury officials in Austria should ab\nstain from politics and devote more time to heading off\nrunaway inflation resulting from the flood of \"occupation\nmarks.\u201d\n7. A voice at the coming Council of Foreign Ministers\nat London, when Austrian frontiers and other interests\ncome up for discussion.\nBy Fred W. Perkins\nwith unemployment declining rapidly.\u201d The Government\nstatisticians say that the peak of unemployment next\nspring should not last more than a few weeks or a few\nmonths, at the most.\nCIO leaders, campaigning for all the unemployment\nlegislation that Congress can be induced to enact, go much\nhigher than the comparatively conservative figures used\nby the AFL.\nR. J. Thomas, president of the CIO United Automobile\nWorkers, told the Senate Finance Committee, which is\nworking on the same subject as the House Ways and\nMeans Committee, that \"gross disemployment\u201d between\nnow and Dec. 31 \u2018will surely be close to double the 6.2\nmillion figure of the War Manpower Commission.\u201d Mr\nThomas\u2019 way of figuring is to count in all the people who\nlose jobs and get others fairly soon, and also all the people,\nincluding women and older men, who \u201cwithdraw from\nthe labor market\" for one reason or another.\nJAMES B. CAREY, secretary-treasurer of the CIO. used\neven bigger figures before the Ways and Means Com\nmittee. Unemployment, he said, is now 3'A millions, altho\nthe War Manpower Commission had just estimated from\ntelegraphic reports that only two million war workers had\nbeen released. It added this was \"not to be regarded in\ntotal as an increase in unemployment, since some of the\nworkers displaced are being absorbed into expanding and\ncontinuing industries.\u201d The WMC figures for areas were\nalmost uniformly lower than those cited in Mr. Thomas'\ntestimony.\nMr. Carey said that \"all Government economists agree\nthat it (the unemployment total) will climb to eight\nmillion by or soon after the first of the year. 1 have\nseen some figures which indicate that in the absence of\nstrong Government programs, unemployment will reach\n16 million by mid-1947.\"\nBy Peter Edson\nMaster minds of the new organization of liberal b. m.\nbear three names well known to Washington:\nMorris S. Rosenthal, executive vice president of Stein\nHall, New York importers. Rosenthal was formerly a\ndirector of the old Board of Economic Warfare under Milo\nPerkins and Henry Wallace. He is to be executive vice\npresident of NCAB.\nThurman Arnold, former trust-busting assistant attorney\ngeneral, recently resigned as associate justice on the Dis\ntrict of Columbia Court of Appeals, is to be NCAB general\ncounsel.\nHoward J. McMurray, former congressman from Mil\nwaukee and before that professor of political science at\nUniversity of Wisconsin, is NCAB executive director and\nhead of its Washington office.\n\u25a0^CAB today makes no boasts about its membership.\nfriends, influence or finances. It is strictly a new\nsociety in the making.\nIf you wgnt to know what a liberal-minded businessman\nis supposed to think or be thinking about in these touchy\ntimes, here are some of the specific proposals which NCAB\nleaders are discussing for inclusion in their platform and\neconomic bill of rights of the 20th Century\";\nFull employment is sound business, so pass the Murraj\nfull-employment bill. Keep taxes high to protect war\nbond holders, but eliminate excess profits and consumers\ntaxes. Enforce the anti-trust laws and strengthen small\nbusiness. Reform the patent system. Expand the TVA\nidea to other river valleys. Provide Federal scholarships\nfor student aid. Provide adequate housing for families\nwith income under SISOO a year. Set up a permanent\nFair Employment Practices Committee. Pass the new\nWagner Social Security bill. Create a national food pro\nduction budget to give the best nutrition to all the people.\nn?E WARMING TOR OAHY I T\nSIDE GLANCES\ncm \\R\nlb\nJ\n\u201c1 hope you don\u2019t think I'm intruding, but will you let me know when\nhe proposes by mail? I've got a bet with the postmaster!'\n3g\nMY DAY\nEnd of Lend-Lease\nCalls for Thought\non Real Situation\nBy ELEANOR ROOSEVELT\nJ-JYDE PARK, Thursday\u2014Now that the first heat of the con\ntroversy over Lend-Lease is at an end, 1 wonder if it might\nnot be good for us as a nation to think over what the real sit\nuation is.\nWe in the United States have a pre-eminent world position.\nWe have it, first, because we were the fortunate nation whose\nhomeland was never touched by any enemy.\nNone of our factories was de\nstroyed. none of our homes bombed,\nand none of our children and civil\nian men and women died from en\nemy action. This was partly due to\nthe fact our men defended us far\nfrom our own shores. But it was\nalso due to the fact that other na\ntions\u2014China in the Far East. Great\nBritain. Russia. France and many\nof the smaller nations in the Euro\npean area\u2014took the first brunt of\nthe war on their shoulders.\nIn the second place, we had the\nresources, wealth and skills among\nour people to develop the greatest\nproduction area the world has ever\nseen. Our resources would have\navailed us little if our people had\nnot been able to use them. The\nbasic wealth of any nation is the skill\nand ability of the people\nWE THEREFORE have today a\nposition of great responsibility\nand with it. of course, the opportu\nnity to gain friends for ourselves\nand make it possible for other na\ntions to live in friendship together\nThru lack of forethought and reali\nzation of our responsibility we may.\nhowever, create discord and dislike\nfor ourselves.\nIn the case of Lend-Lease it is ob\nvious our responsible officials fell\nthey were obligated at the close of\nthe war to bring it to an end. and\nWhen this is where you'd like to be.\nW-\nundoubtedly the other nations were\nacquainted with this fact. Certain\nheads of departments, however\nshould remember human nature is\nsimilar everywhere A disagreeable\nfact is not acknowledged until it is\nnecessary to do so. We allowed our\nselves. it seems to me. to be put in\na position where we could be blamed\ntor what other nations could claim to\nbe hurried readjustments.\nOUR international manners, per\nhaps. need reconsidering. Might\nit have been possible to invite the\nofficials who are now coming to\nWashington to have come before the\nannouncement of the end of Lend-\nLease was made? Might it have been\npossible to get all of the foreign rep\nresentatives together and avail our\nselves of the opportunity to point\nout what had been accomplished bv\njoint co-operation, how grateful we\nwere for what had been done for us\nand how we hoped that what we\nhad done for others would create a\ngreater desire to work co-operativciv\nin the future\u2019 It would have been\ndifficult, then, to claim surprise in\nany official circles.\nThe responsibility for forethought\nand preparation now rests on us. and\nthe peace of the world depends upon\nour accepting the new position which\nwe now hold.\nTry a frosty glass of\nMu\nTEA\n'MAK\u20ac FUN OTME sUN'w.H<ClLklN<\nurge* icto ru ot icep coffee","height":"14343","width":"11130"}}
